@Node "accept" "RxSocket Functions - accept"

  @{b}accept@{ub} - accepts connections

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    sockfd=accept(socketfd,remote)
    <socketfd/N>,<remote/V>

  @{b}Function@{ub}

    The argument 'socketfd' is a socket, created with @{"socket()" LINK "socket"}, bound
    to an address with @{"bind()" LINK "bind"}, and that is listening after a @{"listen()" link "listen"}.

    The function extracts the first connection request on the queue of
    pending connections and creates a new socket with the same
    properties of socketfd.

    If no connection is present on the queue and the socket is not
    marked as non-blocking, accept() blocks until a connection comes.
    If no connection is present on the queue and the socket is marked
    as non-blocking, accept() returns [EWOULDBLOCK].

    The returned socket can be used to accept more connections.
    The original socket remains opened.

    The function fills 'remote' with the @{"sockaddr_in" LINK "Structures"} fields
    of the connected peer.

    The function must be used with STREAM sockets.

    @{"WaitSelect()" LINK "WaitSelect"} can be used to wait for connection, selecting the
    socket for READ.

    The function fails if:

        o [EBADF]       - 'socketfd' is invalid.

        o [EOPNOTSUPP]  - The socket is not of type STREAM.

        o [EWOULDBLOCK] - The socket is marked as non-blocking
                          and no connections are present.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    socketfd - the socket to accept connection on
    remote   - an ARexx stem name

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    sockfd - the new connected socketfd or -1 for failure

 @{b}See@{ub}
   @{"errno()" LINK "errno"}

@EndNode

@Node "Addr2C" "RxSocket Functions - Addr2C"

  @{b}Addr2C@{ub} - converts from dotted to packed chars.

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    packetAddr=Addr2C(addr)
    <addr/N>

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Converts an Internet address, e.g. as returned
    by @{"resolve()" LINK "resolve"} to packed chars.

    Useful when you want to export an address into memory.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    addr - a dotted address

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    packedChar - the address as a packed chars string

@EndNode

@Node "bind" "RxSocket Functions - bind"

  @{b}bind@{ub} - binds a socket to a name

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res=bind(socketfd,name)
    <socketfd/N>,<locale/V>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Assigns a name to an unnamed socket.

    When a socket is created it only exists in the named space
    given by the address family.

    bind() gives a name to the socket.

    'name' must be set as @{"sockaddr_in" LINK "Structures"}.
    ADDRADDR may be as 0 or not set at all, e.g. for DGRAM sockets.

    The function fails if:

        o [EBADF]         - 'socketfd' is invalid.

        o [EADDRNOTAVAIL] - The specified address is not available
                            from the local machine.

        o [EADDRINUSE]    - The specified address is already in use.

        o [EINVAL]        - The socket is already bound to an
                            address.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    socketfd - the socket to bind to 'name'
    name     - a sockaddr_in to bind the socket to

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - 0 for success, -1 for failure

  @{b}Example@{ub}
    sock = socket("INET","DGRAM","IP")
    if sock<0 then do
        say "cannot open socket:" errno()
        exit
    end

    local.ADDRFAMILY = "INET"
    local.ADDRADDR = 0
    local.ADDRPORT = 4000
    if bind(sock,"LOCAL")<0 then do
        say "cannot allocate port 4000:" Errno()
        exit
    end

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"accept()" LINK "accept"} @{"listen()" LINK "listen"} @{"errno()" LINK "errno"}

@EndNode

@Node "CloseRxsCon" "RxSocket Functions - CloseRxsCon"

  @{b}CloseRxsCon@{ub} - closes the global RxSocket console

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res=CloseRxsCon(attempt)
    <attempt/N>

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Closes the global RxSocket console.

    'attempt' is an ARexx boolean:

        o if 'attempt' is omitted it is assumed to be 0

        o if 'attempt' is 0, the function wait till all the console
          users release it.

        o if 'attempt' is not 0, the function doesn't wait and the
          console is closed iff it is not busy.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    attempt - the way the console is closed, see above

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - 0 the console was not closed, 1 it was

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"OpenRxsCon()" LINK "OpenRxsCon"} @{"WriteRxsCon()" LINK "WriteRxsCon"}

@EndNode

@Node "CloseRxSocket" "RxSocket Functions - CloseRxSocket"

  @{b}CloseRxSocket@{ub} - closes local structures

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = CloseRxSocket()
    -

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    When the TCP/IP stack is closed, it sends a ctrl_c to all the
    processes that are using its libraries. It means that even if
    your macros closed all the sockets it may receive a ctrl_c
    and so be compelled to exit. To prevent that, you may use
    this function. It will try to close all the libraries bases,
    so that you may go on without any problem. CloseRxSocket()
    will also close all RxLibnet libraries.

    WARNING: all bsdsocket.library options set are lost.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean that indicates if all the libraries
          base were closes.

@EndNode

@Node "CloseSocket" "RxSocket Functions - CloseSocket"

  @{b}CloseSocket@{ub} - closes a socket

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res=CloseSocket(socketfd)
    <socketfd/N>

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Closes a socket.

    Sockets are closed when the macro exits, but, because of the
    per-macro max number of opened sockets is limited, it is useful
    to close a socket when it is not needed anymore.

    The function may fail if:

        o [EBADF] - 'socketfd' is invalid

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    socketfd - a socket descriptor

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - 0 for success, -1 for failure

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"ShutDown()" LINK "ShutDown"} @{"errno()" LINK "errno"}

@EndNode

@Node "connect" "RxSocket Functions - connect"

  @{b}connect@{ub} - connects a socket

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res=connect(socketfd,remote)
    <socketfd/N>,<remote/V>

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Connects the socket to the @{"socketaddr_in" LINK "Structures"} as defined in 'remote'.

    If the socket is DGRAM, the function specified the peer with which
    the socket is associated: the address specified is that to which
    datagram are sent and from which datagram are received.

    If the socket is STREAM, the function tries to make a connection
    to another socket as specified in 'remote'.

    STREAM sockets may connect only once.

    DGRAM sockets may connect multiple times to change their
    association and connect to a invalid address to dissolve it.

    The function may fail if:

        o [EBADF]         - 'socketfd' is invalid.

        o [EADDRNOTAVAIL] - The specified address is not available on
                            this machine.

        o [EAFNOSUPPORT]  - Addresses in the specified address family
                            cannot be used with this socket.

        o [EISCONN]       - The socket is already connected.

        o [ETIMEDOUT]     - Connection timeout.

        o [ECONNREFUSED]  - The attempt to connect was forcefully
                            rejected.

        o [ENETUNREACH]   - The network isn't reachable from this host.

        o [EADDRINUSE]    - The address is already in use.

        o [EINPROGRESS]   - The socket is non-blocking and
                            the connection cannot be completed
                            immediately. It is possible to
                            WaitSelect() for completion by
                            selecting the socket for writing.

        o [EALREADY]      - The socket is non-blocking and a previous
                            connection attempt has not yet been
                            completed.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    socketfd - the socket to connect
    remote   - an ARexx stem name set as a sockaddr_in

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - 0 for success, -1 for failure

  @{b}Example@{ub}
    sin.addrFamily = "INET"
    sin.addrPort   = 80
    sin.addrAddr   = addr
    if connect(sockfd,"SIN")<0 then do
        say "connect: error" Errno()
        exit
    end

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"errno()" LINK "errno"}

@EndNode

@Node "Dup2Socket" "RxSocket Functions - Dup2Socket"

  @{b}Dup2Socket@{ub} - duplicates a socket

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    sockfd=Dup2Socket(socketfd,newsockfd)
    <socketfd/N>,[newsockfd/N]

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Duplicates an existing socket and returns the new socketfd.
    A new internal socket resource is allocated.
    If 'newsockfd' is not given, it is assumed to be -1.

    The function may fail if:

        o [EBADF] - 'socketfd' or 'newsockfd' is invalid

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    socketfd  - the socket to duplicate
    newsockfd - the new socket descriptor

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - 0 for success, -1 for failure

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"errno()" LINK "errno"}

@EndNode

@Node "errno" "RxSocket Functions - errno"

  @{b}errno@{ub} - returns the current bsdsocket.library error.

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    error=errno()
    -

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Returns the current error code, one of:

        o EPERM            1      Operation not permitted
        o ENOENT           2      No such file or directory
        o ESRCH            3      No such process
        o EINTR            4      Interrupted system call
        o EIO              5      Input/output error
        o ENXIO            6      Device not configured
        o E2BIG            7      Argument list too long
        o ENOEXEC          8      Exec format error
        o EBADF            9      Bad file descriptor
        o ECHILD          10      No child processes
        o EDEADLK         11      Resource deadlock avoided
        o ENOMEM          12      Cannot allocate memory
        o EACCES          13      Permission denied
        o EFAULT          14      Bad address
        o ENOTBLK         15      Block device required
        o EBUSY           16      Device busy
        o EEXIST          17      File exists
        o EXDEV           18      Cross-device link
        o ENODEV          19      Operation not supported by device
        o ENOTDIR         20      Not a directory
        o EISDIR          21      Is a directory
        o EINVAL          22      Invalid argument
        o ENFILE          23      Too many open files in system
        o EMFILE          24      Too many open files
        o ENOTTY          25      Inappropriate ioctl for device
        o ETXTBSY         26      Text file busy
        o EFBIG           27      File too large
        o ENOSPC          28      No space left on device
        o ESPIPE          29      Illegal seek
        o EROFS           30      Read-only file system
        o EMLINK          31      Too many links
        o EPIPE           32      Broken pipe
        o EDOM            33      Numerical argument out of domain
        o ERANGE          34      Result too large
        o EAGAIN          35      Resource temporarily unavailable
        o EWOULDBLOCK     35      Operation would block
        o EINPROGRESS     36      Operation now in progress
        o EALREADY        37      Operation already in progress
        o ENOTSOCK        38      Socket operation on non-socket
        o EDESTADDRREQ    39      Destination address required
        o EMSGSIZE        40      Message too long
        o EPROTOTYPE      41      Protocol wrong type for socket
        o ENOPROTOOPT     42      Protocol not available
        o EPROTONOSUPPORT 43      Protocol not supported
        o ESOCKTNOSUPPORT 44      Socket type not supported
        o EOPNOTSUPP      45      Operation not supported
        o EPFNOSUPPORT    46      Protocol family not supported
        o EAFNOSUPPORT    47      Address family not supported by protocol family
        o EADDRINUSE      48      Address already in use
        o EADDRNOTAVAIL   49      Can't assign requested address
        o ENETDOWN        50      Network is down
        o ENETUNREACH     51      Network is unreachable
        o ENETRESET       52      Network dropped connection on reset
        o ECONNABORTED    53      Software caused connection abort
        o ECONNRESET      54      Connection reset by peer
        o ENOBUFS         55      No buffer space available
        o EISCONN         56      Socket is already connected
        o ENOTCONN        57      Socket is not connected
        o ESHUTDOWN       58      Can't send after socket shutdown
        o ETOOMANYREFS    59      Too many references: can't splice
        o ETIMEDOUT       60      Operation timed out
        o ECONNREFUSED    61      Connection refused
        o ELOOP           62      Too many levels of symbolic links
        o ENAMETOOLONG    63      File name too long
        o EHOSTDOWN       64      Host is down
        o EHOSTUNREACH    65      No route to host
        o ENOTEMPTY       66      Directory not empty
        o EPROCLIM        67      Too many processes
        o EUSERS          68      Too many users
        o EDQUOT          69      Disc quota exceeded
        o ESTALE          70      Stale NFS file handle
        o EREMOTE         71      Too many levels of remote in path
        o EBADRPC         72      RPC struct is bad
        o ERPCMISMATCH    73      RPC version wrong
        o EPROGUNAVAIL    74      RPC prog. not avail
        o EPROGMISMATCH   75      Program version wrong
        o EPROCUNAVAIL    76      Bad procedure for program
        o ENOLCK          77      No locks available
        o ENOSYS          78      @{b}Function@{ub} not implemented
        o EFTYPE          79      Inappropriate file type or format
        o EAUTH           80      Authentication error
        o ENEEDAUTH       81      Need authenticator

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    none

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    error - the current error code

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"ErrorString()" LINK "ErrorString"}

@EndNode

@Node "ErrorString" "RxSocket Functions - ErrorString"

  @{b}ErrorString@{ub} - returns the string associated with an error code.

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    errorString=ErrorString(code)
    [code/N]

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Returns the error string associated with 'code'.
    If 'code' is omitted, it is assumed to be the current
    error code.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    code - the id of the error

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    errorString - the string associated with 'code'

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"errno()" LINK "errno"}

@EndNode

@Node "FreeLineRead" "RxSocket Functions - FreeLineRead"

  @{b}FreeLineRead@{ub} - free a LineRead

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    call FreeLineRead(socketfd)
    <socketfd/N>

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Free all resources allocated with @{"InitLineRead()" LINK InitLineRead}.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    socketfd - the socket associated with the LineRead to free

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"InitLineRead()" LINK "InitLineRead"} @{"LineRead()" LINK "LineRead"}

@EndNode

@Node "GetHost" "RxSocket Functions - GetHost"

  @{b}GetHost@{ub} - returns host information

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res=GetHost(host,name)
    <host/V>,<name>

  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Fills 'host' with a @{"hostent" LINK "Structures"} data, host given as addr or name.

    @{"HostErrorno()" LINK "HostErrorno"} can be used to get the host-lookup
    error code on failure.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    host - an ARexx stem name
    name - a host name or a dotted address to find information about

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"GetHostByAddr()" LINK "GetHostByAddr"} @{"GetHostByName()" LINK "GetHostByName"}

@EndNode

